<li id="cite_note-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.wfduk.org/sites/default/files/Media/170116%20Substance%20Determinationsfinal.pdf">"Substance determinations"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. <i>Water Framework Directive</i>. JAGDAG/Environment Agency<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">28 March</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Water+Framework+Directive&amp;rft.atitle=Substance+determinations&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wfduk.org%2Fsites%2Fdefault%2Ffiles%2FMedia%2F170116%2520Substance%2520Determinationsfinal.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFracking+in+the+United+Kingdom" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-45"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFHardy2014" class="citation book cs1">Hardy, Peter (1 January 2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/chapterhtml/2014/9781782620556-00001?isbn=978-1-78262-055-6">"CHAPTER 1. Introduction and Overview: the Role of Shale Gas in Securing Our Energy Future"</a>. <i>Fracking</i>. Issues in Environmental Science and Technology. Royal Society of Chemistry. pp.&#160;145. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.1039%2F9781782620556-00001">10.1039/9781782620556-00001</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-84973-920-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-84973-920-7"><bdi>978-1-84973-920-7</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">28 March</span> 2017</span>. <q>The fracturing fluid that Cuadrilla has used at the Preese Hall exploration well site, and plans to use at future exploration well sites, is composed almost entirely of fresh water and sand.  Cuadrilla also has approval to use the following additives: Polyacrylamide (friction reducer) Sodium salt (for tracing fracturing fluid) Hydrochloric acid (diluted with water) Glutaraldehyde biocide (used to cleanse water and remove bacteria) So far, as additives to fracturing fluid, Cuadrilla has only used polyacrylamide friction reducer along with a minuscule amount of salt, which acts as a tracer. Cuadrilla have not needed to use biocide as the water supplied by United Utilities to their Lancashire exploration well sites has already been treated to remove bacteria, nor have they used diluted hydrochloric acid in fracturing fluid.  Additives proposed, in the quantities proposed, have resulted in the fracturing fluid being classified as non-hazardous by the Environment Agency.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=CHAPTER+1.+Introduction+and+Overview%3A+the+Role+of+Shale+Gas+in+Securing+Our+Energy+Future&amp;rft.btitle=Fracking&amp;rft.series=Issues+in+Environmental+Science+and+Technology&amp;rft.pages=1-45&amp;rft.pub=Royal+Society+of+Chemistry&amp;rft.date=2014-01-01&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1039%2F9781782620556-00001&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-84973-920-7&amp;rft.aulast=Hardy&amp;rft.aufirst=Peter&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fpubs.rsc.org%2Fen%2Fcontent%2Fchapterhtml%2F2014%2F9781782620556-00001%3Fisbn%3D978-1-78262-055-6&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFracking+in+the+United+Kingdom" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFBroderickAndersonWoodGilbert2011" class="citation web cs1">Broderick, Dr John; Anderson, Professor Kevin; Wood, Dr Ruth; Gilbert, Dr Paul; Sharmina, Mrs Maria; Footitt, Mr Anthony; Glynn, Dr Steven; Nicholls, Ms Fiona (November 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.mace.manchester.ac.uk/media/eps/schoolofmechanicalaerospaceandcivilengineering/newsandevents/news/research/pdfs2011/shale-gas-threat-report.pdf">"Shale gas: an updated assessment of environmental and climate change impacts"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. The University of Manchester, Tyndall Centre for Climate Change Research. p.&#160;24<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">30 March</span> 2017</span>. <q>Table 2.4: Composition of Fracking Fluid for Preese Hall Well 1. Total of 6 frack stages</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Shale+gas%3A+an+updated+assessment+of+environmental+and+climate+change+impacts&amp;rft.pages=24&amp;rft.pub=The+University+of+Manchester%2C+Tyndall+Centre+for+Climate+Change+Research&amp;rft.date=2011-11&amp;rft.aulast=Broderick&amp;rft.aufirst=Dr+John&amp;rft.au=Anderson%2C+Professor+Kevin&amp;rft.au=Wood%2C+Dr+Ruth&amp;rft.au=Gilbert%2C+Dr+Paul&amp;rft.au=Sharmina%2C+Mrs+Maria&amp;rft.au=Footitt%2C+Mr+Anthony&amp;rft.au=Glynn%2C+Dr+Steven&amp;rft.au=Nicholls%2C+Ms+Fiona&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.mace.manchester.ac.uk%2Fmedia%2Feps%2Fschoolofmechanicalaerospaceandcivilengineering%2Fnewsandevents%2Fnews%2Fresearch%2Fpdfs2011%2Fshale-gas-threat-report.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFracking+in+the+United+Kingdom" class="Z3988"></span></span>
