<li id="cite_note-53"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-53">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFDavies" class="citation web cs1">Davies; et&#160;al. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.refine.org.uk/media/sites/researchwebsites/1refine/papers/Davies,%202012%20-%20Hydraulic%20Fractures%20-%20how%20far%20can%20they%20go.pdf">"Hydraulic fractures: How far can they go?"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. ReFine. p.&#160;1<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">22 February</span> 2017</span>. <q><span class="cs1-kern-left"></span>"The maximum reported height of an upward propagating hydraulic fracture from several thousand fracturing operations in the Marcellus, Barnett, Woodford, Eagle Ford and Niobrara shale (USA) is 588 m. Based on these empirical data, the probability of a stimulated hydraulic fracture extending vertically less than 350 m is less than 1%. Constraining the probability of stimulating unusually tall hydraulic fractures in sedimentary rocks is extremely important as an evidence base for decisions on the safe vertical separation between the depth of stimulation and rock strata not intended for penetration".</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Hydraulic+fractures%3A+How+far+can+they+go%3F&amp;rft.pages=1&amp;rft.pub=ReFine&amp;rft.au=Davies&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.refine.org.uk%2Fmedia%2Fsites%2Fresearchwebsites%2F1refine%2Fpapers%2FDavies%2C%25202012%2520-%2520Hydraulic%2520Fractures%2520-%2520how%2520far%2520can%2520they%2520go.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFracking+in+the+United+Kingdom" class="Z3988"></span></span>
